<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-800-928  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 800 928.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Digital Review  August 20 1990 v7 n32 p4(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Cahners-Ziff Publishing Associates LP 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>4Mbit chips boost SI solid-state disks. (System Industries Inc.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Kovsky, Steven.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   System Industries Inc. (product development).andO;Ticker:    SYI.andO;Topic:     Product DevelopmentDisk DrivesRAM.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>4Mbit chips boost SI solid-state disksandM;MILPITAS, Calif.andP;  -- System Industries (SI) last week announced that 4Mbitdynamic RAM chips are now available for its MegaRam solid-state diskproducts, effectively quadrupling the capacity of the MegaRam to more than2GB.andM;The MegaRam products are manufactured by former System Industries subsidiaryImperial Technology, which was recently spun out of SI and purchased by agroup of Imperial's managers.andM;SI has exclusive rights to resell Imperial products for the DEC marketplace.andM;The 4Mbit memory chips enable Imperial to expand the capacity of a singlequad-sized board from 32MB to 128MB.andM;Port accesses 2BG of RAMandM;Fully configured with 128MB boards, a single HSC requestor port can nowaccess 2GB worth of RAM, according to an SI spokesman.andM;The MegaRam devices are also available for use with DEC Q-bus and Unibus hostadapters.andM;In addition to increasing the capacity of the MegaRam products, the 4Mbitchips have also decreased in price.andP;  Use of the more economical,higher-capacity chips has allowed SI to drop the price by 16 percent forMegaRam subsystems with at least 128MB of RAM.andM;A 128MB MegaRam device was previously priced at $87,700, compared with thedevice's current list price of $73,900.andM;For additional information, System Industries Inc. can be contacted at 1855Barber Lane, Milpitas, CA 95035, (408) 432-1212.andO;</TEXT></DOC>